4.25/5  rDev -7.8%look: 4.25 | smell: 4.25 | taste: 4.25 | feel: 4.25 |  overall: 4.2533cl pour at Cafe In de Vrede (Westvleteren, Belgium)
Typical dark fruits associated with quadrupels are at play on the initial aroma. Dark plums, dates, candied fruits, and maybe figs is well supported by hints of spice, and bready Belgian yeast. A sweet wine like aftertaste also develops as the brew gets warmer. Perhaps more brandy than sweet wine.
I guess this is where the beer earns its hyped title. Lots of dark fruits, burnt sugar, cracked pepper, dates, and figs on the tongue at first. Molasses and a light licorice-like flavor takes over mid-tongue, leaving behind a subtly sweet candi sugar and cherry like flavor. Didn't occur to me the last two times I've tried this, but there is a very subtle muted hop flavor that resides in the back burner.
Nice dry, bitter finish, full-bodied with a pleasant amount of carbonation. 838 charactersamano_h, Jun 08, 2014
